:= by\n        have h₈₁ : rule ∈ f i := by\n          simp_all [List.any]\n        have h₈₂ : List.find? rule (f i) < (f i).length := by\n          apply List.findLT\n          <;> simp_all [List.any]\n        exact h₈₂\n      use ⟨List.find? rule (f i), h₈⟩\n      have h₉ : (f i).get ⟨List.find? rule (f i), h₈⟩ = rule := by\n        have h₉₁ : List.find? rule (f i) < (f i).length := h₈\n        have h₉₂ : (List.get? (f i) (List.find? rule (f i))).getD (default : RelInt S) = rule := by\n          have h₉₃ : (List.get? (f i) (List.find? rule (f i))) = Some rule := by\n            rw [List.get?_find?]\n            <;> simp_all [List.any]\n            <;> aesop\n          rw [h₉₃]\n          <;> simp_all\n        have h₉₃ : (f i).get ⟨List.find? rule (f i), h₈⟩ = rule := by\n          have h₉₄ : (List.get? (f i) (List.find? rule (f i))) = Some ((f i).get ⟨List.find? rule (f i), h₈⟩) := by\n            simp_all [List.get?_get]\n          simp_all\n          <;> aesop\n        exact h₉₃\n      simp_all\n      <;> aesop\n    exact h₆\n  obtain ⟨j, hj⟩ := h₄\n  refine' ⟨i, j, _⟩\n  simp_all [hj]\n  <;> aesop",
      "`List.mem_map`, `∃ (y : Fin n), y ∈ fin_range n ∧ f y = l`.\n4. But by `fin_in_fin_range`, we know that all `y : Fin n` are in `fin_range n`, so the condition is redundant and we can get `∃ (y : Fin n), f y = l`.\n5. Since `rule ∈ l` and `l = f y`, we have `rule ∈ f y`, which in turn implies `∃ (j : Fin (f y).length), rule = (f y).get j`.\n\nHowever, in Lean, `List.mem_map` gives us `∃ (y : Fin n), y ∈ fin_range n ∧ f y = l`, and it's not immediately obvious how to drop the `y ∈ fin_range n` condition. \n\nBut perhaps we can use that:\n - For any `y : Fin n`, `y ∈ fin_range n` is true (from `fin_in_fin_range`).\n - So if we have `∃ (y : Fin n), y ∈ fin_range n ∧ f y = l`, then in fact `∃ (y : Fin n), f y = l`.\n\nAlternatively:\n - To prove `∃ (y : Fin n), f y = l`, given `∃ (y : Fin n), y ∈ fin_range n ∧ f y = l`, we just take the same `y`, knowing that `y ∈ fin_range n` is automatically satisfied because `y : Fin n`. So the `y ∈ fin_range n` part is redundant.\n\nThus, step 3 can become:\n - `l ∈ (fin_range n).map f` implies `∃ (y : Fin n), f y = l`.\n\nBut really, the statement of `List.mem_map` is `x ∈ l.map f ↔ ∃ y ∈ l, f y = x`. Here `x = l`, `l = (fin_range n)`, and `f = f`, but this is confusing notation-wise.\n\nActually, the right way is:\n\nWe have `l ∈ (fin_range n).map f`. By `List.mem_map`, this means there exists `y ∈ (fin_range n)` such that `f y = l`. \nBut any `y : Fin n` is in `(fin_range n)` because of `fin_in_fin_range`. \nThus, for any `y : Fin n`, `y ∈ (fin_range n)`, and we can simply say that there exists a `y : Fin n` such that `f y = l`.\n\nBut in Lean, given `∃ (y : Fin n), y ∈ (fin_range n) ∧ f y = l`, we can actually just use `Classical.choose` to get `y : Fin n`, and we don't need to care about the `y ∈ (fin_range n)` because we know it is true.\n\n### Conclusion:\nThe formal proof will proceed as follows:\n1. Use `List.mem_flatten` on the hypothesis `h : rule ∈ (fin_range n.map f).flatten` to get `∃ l, l ∈ (fin_range n).map f ∧ rule ∈ l`.\n2. For each such `l`, use `List.mem_map` on `l ∈ (fin_range n).map f` to get `∃",
      "\n  intro h\n  simp only [RelInt.liftFinf, List.mem_flatten] at h\n  obtain ⟨i, hi⟩ := h\n  obtain ⟨j, hj⟩ := hi\n  refine' ⟨i, j, _⟩\n  <;> simp_all [List.get]\n  <;> aesop",
      "\n  intro h_in\n  have h₁ : rule ∈ fin_range n |>.map f |>.flatten := by\n    simpa [RelInt.liftFinf] using h_in\n  have h₂ : rule ∈ List.bind (fin_range n |>.map f) (λ l => l) := by\n    simpa [List.bind] using h₁\n  have h₃ : rule ∈ List.bind (fin_range n |>.map f) (λ l => l) := h₂\n  have h₄ : ∃ (l : List (RelInt S)), l ∈ fin_range n |>.map f ∧ rule ∈ l := by\n    simp only [List.bind_eq_bind, List.mem_bind] at h₃\n    obtain ⟨l, hl, hr⟩ := h₃\n    exact ⟨l, hl, hr⟩\n  obtain ⟨l, hl, hr⟩ := h₄\n  have h₅ : ∃ (i : Fin n), f i = l := by\n    have h₅₁ : l ∈ fin_range n |>.map f := hl\n    simp only [List.mem_map] at h₅₁\n    obtain ⟨x, hx, rfl⟩ := h₅₁\n    exact ⟨x, by simp_all⟩\n  obtain ⟨i, hi⟩ := h₅\n  have h₆ : rule ∈ f i := by\n    rw [hi] at hr\n    exact hr\n  have h₇ : ∃ (j : Fin (f i).length), rule = (f i).get j := by\n    have h₇₁ : rule ∈ f i := h₆\n    have h₇₂ : ∃ (j : Fin (f i).length), (f i).get j = rule := by\n      have h₇₃ : ∃ (j : Fin (f i).length), (f i).get j = rule := by\n        have h₇₄ : rule ∈ f i := h₆\n        have h₇₅ : ∃ (j : Fin (f i).length), (f i).get j = rule := by\n          classical\n          have h₇₆ : rule ∈ f i := h₆\n          have h₇₇ : ∃ (j : Fin (f i).length), (f i).get j = rule := by\n            -- Use the fact that the list is nonempty to find the index\n            have h₇₈ : 0 < (f i).length ∨ (f i).length = 0 := by omega\n            cases h₇₈ with\n            | inl h₇₈ =>\n              -- Case: the list is nonempty\n              have h₇₉ : ∃ (j : Fin (f i).length), (f i).get j = rule := by\n                classical\n                -- Use the Axiom of Choice to find the index\n                use List.find (List.findP (fun x : RelInt S => x = rule) (f i))\n                  (by\n                    have h₈₀ : rule ∈ f i := h₆\n                    have h₈₁ : ∃ (x : RelInt S), x ∈ f i ∧ x = rule := ⟨rule, h₈₀, rfl⟩\n                    have h₈₂ : ∃ (x : RelInt S), x ∈ f i ∧ x = rule := h₈₁\n                    -- Use the fact that the list is nonempty to find the index\n                    have h₈₃ : ∃ (x : RelInt S), x ∈ f i ∧ x = rule := h₈₂\n                    have h₈₄ : ∃ (x : RelInt S), x ∈ f i ∧ x = rule := h₈₃\n                    simpa [List.exists]\n                      using h₈₄)\n                <;>\n                  simp_all [List.findP, List.get]\n                <;>\n                  aesop\n              exact h₇₉\n            | inr h₇₈ =>\n              -- Case: the list is empty\n              exfalso\n              have h₇₉ : rule ∈ f i := h₆\n              simp_all [h₇₈, List.mem_nil_iff]\n          exact h₇₇\n        exact h₇₅\n      exact h₇₃\n    obtain ⟨j, hj⟩ := h₇₂\n    refine' ⟨j, _⟩\n    rw [hj]\n    <;> simp_all\n  obtain ⟨j, hj⟩ := h₇\n  refine' ⟨i, j, _⟩\n  <;> simp_all [hj]\n  <;> aesop",
      "\n      intro h\n      have h₁ : rule ∈ (fin_range n).map f |>.flatten := by simpa [RelInt.liftFinf] using h\n      have h₂ : ∃ (i : List (RelInt S)), i ∈ (fin_range n).map f ∧ rule ∈ i := by\n        simp only [List.mem_flatten] at h₁ ⊢\n        exact h₁\n      obtain ⟨i, hi₁, hi₂⟩ := h₂\n      have h₃ : ∃ (x : Fin n), i = f x := by\n        simp only [List.mem_map] at hi₁\n        obtain ⟨x, hx, rfl⟩ := hi₁\n        refine' ⟨x, _⟩\n        <;> simp_all [fin_range_eq]\n        <;> aesop\n      obtain ⟨x, hx⟩ := h₃\n      have h₄ : ∃ (j : Fin (f x).length), rule = (f x).get j := by\n        have h₅ : rule ∈ f x := by\n          rw [hx] at hi₂\n          exact hi₂\n        have h₆ : ∃ (j : Fin (f x).length), (f x).get j = rule := by\n          apply List.mem_iff_get.mp\n          exact h₅\n        obtain ⟨j, hj⟩ := h₆\n        refine' ⟨j, _⟩\n        rw [hj]\n        <;> simp [eq_comm]\n      obtain ⟨j, hj⟩ := h₄\n      refine' ⟨x, j, _⟩\n      rw [hx] at *\n      exact hj\n\n  end RelInt\n\nend Graphiti.Projects.Noc",
      "\n  intro h\n  have h₁ : ∃ (l' : List (RelInt S)), l' ∈ (fin_range n).map f ∧ rule ∈ l' := by\n    have h₂ : rule ∈ ((fin_range n).map f).flatten := by simpa [RelInt.liftFinf] using h\n    have h₃ : ∃ (l' : List (RelInt S)), l' ∈ (fin_range n).map f ∧ rule ∈ l' := by\n      rw [List.mem_flatten] at h₂\n      obtain ⟨l', hl', hrule⟩ := h₂\n      refine' ⟨l', hl', hrule⟩\n    exact h₃\n  \n  have h₂ : ∃ (i : Fin n), rule ∈ f i := by\n    obtain ⟨l', hl', hrule⟩ := h₁\n    have h₃ : l' ∈ (fin_range n).map f := hl'\n    have h₄ : ∃ (i : Fin n), f i = l' := by\n      rw [List.mem_map] at h₃\n      obtain ⟨i, hi, rfl⟩ := h₃\n      refine' ⟨i, _⟩\n      <;> simp_all\n    obtain ⟨i, hi⟩ := h₄\n    have h₅ : rule ∈ f i := by\n      rw [hi] at hrule\n      exact hrule\n    exact ⟨i, h₅⟩\n  \n  have h₃ : ∃ (i : Fin n) (j : Fin (f i).length), rule = (f i).get j := by\n    obtain ⟨i, hi⟩ := h₂\n    have h₄ : ∃ (j : Fin (f i).length), rule = (f i).get j := by\n      have h₅ : rule ∈ f i := hi\n      have h₆ : ∃ (j : Fin (f i).length), rule = (f i).get j := by\n        rw [List.mem_iff_get] at h₅\n        obtain ⟨j, hj⟩ := h₅\n        refine' ⟨j, _⟩\n        <;> simp_all [List.get]\n        <;> aesop\n      exact h₆\n    obtain ⟨j, hj⟩ := h₄\n    exact ⟨i, j, by simp_all [hj]⟩\n  \n  exact h₃",
      "\n      intro h\n      have h₁ : rule ∈ (fin_range n |>.map f |>.flatten : List (RelInt S)) := by simpa [RelInt.liftFinf] using h\n      have h₂ : rule ∈ (fin_range n |>.map f |>.flatten : List (RelInt S)) → ∃ (i : Fin n) (j : Fin (f i).length), rule = (f i).get j := by\n        intro h₃\n        have h₄ : ∀ {α : Type} (a : α) (l : List α), a ∈ l → ∀ (f : α → List β) (l : List α), a ∈ l → ∀ (g : β → Prop) (b : β), b ∈ (l.map f).flatten → ∃ (x : α) (y : ℕ), b ∈ f x ∧ y < (f x).length ∧ b = (f x).get ⟨y, ‹y < (f x).length›⟩ := by\n          intro α a l h₅ β f l' h₆ g b h₇\n          have h₈ : b ∈ (l'.map f).flatten := h₇\n          have h₉ : ∃ (x : α) (y : ℕ), b ∈ f x ∧ y < (f x).length ∧ b = (f x).get ⟨y, ‹y < (f x).length›⟩ := by\n            -- We need to find an element x in l' and an index y such that b is in f x and y < (f x).length and b = (f x).get ⟨y, ‹y < (f x).length›⟩\n            -- This can be done by using the fact that b is in the flattened list of l'.map f\n            have h₁₀ : b ∈ (l'.map f).flatten := h₈\n            have h₁₁ : ∃ (x : α) (l : List β), x ∈ l' ∧ l = f x ∧ b ∈ l := by\n              -- We need to find an x in l' and a list l = f x such that b is in l\n              -- This can be done by using the fact that b is in the flattened list of l'.map f\n              classical\n              have h₁₂ : b ∈ (l'.map f).flatten := h₁₀\n              have h₁₃ : ∃ (l : List β), l ∈ (l'.map f) ∧ b ∈ l := by\n                -- Since b is in the flattened list, it must be in one of the lists in l'.map f\n                rw [List.mem_flatten] at h₁₂\n                obtain ⟨l, h₁₄, h₁₅⟩ := h₁₂\n                refine' ⟨l, _⟩\n                <;> simp_all\n              obtain ⟨l, h₁₄, h₁₅⟩ := h₁₃\n              have h₁₆ : l ∈ (l'.map f) := h₁₄\n              have h₁₇ : b ∈ l := h₁₅\n              have h₁₈ : ∃ (x : α), x ∈ l' ∧ l = f x := by\n                -- Since l is in l'.map f, there exists an x in l' such that l = f x\n                simp only [List.mem_map] at h₁₆\n                obtain ⟨x, h₁₉, rfl⟩ := h₁₆\n                exact ⟨x, h₁₉, rfl⟩\n              obtain ⟨x, h₂₀, h₂₁⟩ := h₁₈\n              refine' ⟨x, l, h₂₀, h₂₁, h₁₇⟩\n            obtain ⟨x, l, h₂₂, h₂₃, h₂₄⟩ := h₁₁\n            have h₂₅ : l = f x := h₂₃\n            have h₂₆ : b ∈ l := h₂₄\n            have h₂₇ : x ∈ l' := h₂₂\n            have h₂₈ : b ∈ f x := by simp_all\n            have h₂₉ : ∃ (y : ℕ), y < (f x).length ∧ b = (f x).get ⟨y, ‹y < (f x).length›⟩ := by\n              -- Since b is in f x, there exists an index y such that b = (f x).get ⟨y, ‹y < (f x).length›⟩\n              classical\n              have h₃₀ : b ∈ f x := h₂₈\n              have h₃₁ : ∃ (y : ℕ), y < (f x).length ∧ b = (f x).get ⟨y, ‹y < (f x).length›⟩ := by\n                -- We can find such a y by using the fact that b is in f x\n                have h₃₂ : b ∈ f x := h₃₀\n                have h₃₃ : ∃ (y : ℕ), y < (f x).length ∧ (f x).get ⟨y, ‹y < (f x).length›⟩ = b := by\n                  -- We can find such a y by using the fact that b is in f x\n                  classical\n                  have h₃₄ : b ∈ f x := h₃₂\n                  have h₃₅ : ∃ (y : ℕ), y < (f x).length ∧ (f x).get ⟨y, ‹y < (f x).length›⟩ = b := by\n                    -- We can find such a y by using the fact that b is in f x\n                    simp only [List.mem_iff_get] at h₃₄\n                    obtain ⟨y, h₃₆, h₃₇⟩ := h₃₄\n                    refine' ⟨y, _, _⟩ <;> simp_all [List.get]\n                    <;> try { contradiction } <;> try { linarith }\n                  exact h₃₅\n                obtain ⟨y, h₃₈, h₃₉⟩ := h₃₃\n                refine' ⟨y, h₃₈, _⟩\n                <;> simp_all [List.get]\n                <;> try { contradiction } <;> try { linarith }\n              exact h₃₁\n            obtain ⟨y, h₃₀, h₃₁⟩ := h₂₉\n            refine' ⟨x, y, _, h₃₀, _⟩ <;> simp_all\n          exact h₉\n        have h₅ : rule ∈ (fin_range n |>.map f : List (List (RelInt S))).flatten := by simpa using h₁\n        have h₆ : ∃ (i : Fin n) (j : Fin (f i).length), rule = (f i).get j := by\n          have h₇ : ∀ (a : RelInt S) {l : List (RelInt S)} (h : a ∈ l) (f : (RelInt S) → List (RelInt S)) (l : List (RelInt S)), a ∈ l → ∀ (g : (RelInt S) → Prop) (b : RelInt S), b ∈ (l.map f).flatten → ∃ (x : RelInt S) (y : ℕ), b ∈ f x ∧ y < (f x).length ∧ b = (f x).get ⟨y, ‹y < (f x).length›⟩ := by\n            intro a l h f l' h' g b h'' \n            apply h₄\n          -- We use the helper lemma to find the required indices\n          have h₈ : ∃ (i : Fin n) (j : ℕ), rule ∈ f i ∧ j < (f i).length ∧ rule = (f i).get ⟨j, ‹j < (f i).length›⟩ := by\n            have h₉ : rule ∈ (fin_range n |>.map f : List (List (RelInt S))).flatten := h₅\n            have h₁₀ : ∃ (x : Fin n) (y : ℕ), rule ∈ f x ∧ y < (f x).length ∧ rule = (f x).get ⟨y, ‹y < (f x).length›⟩ := by\n              have h₁₁ := h₄ rule (by simpa using h₁) (fun x => f x) (fin_range n) (by simpa using h₁) (fun x => x = rule) rule h₉\n              simpa using h₁₁\n            obtain ⟨x, y, h₁₁, h₁₂, h₁₃⟩ := h₁₀\n            refine' ⟨x, y, _, _, _⟩ <;> simp_all\n          obtain ⟨i, j, h₉, h₁₀, h₁₁⟩ := h₈\n          refine' ⟨i, ⟨j, h₁₀⟩, _⟩\n          simp_all [List.get]\n          <;> try { contradiction } <;> try { linarith }\n        exact h₆\n      exact h₂ h₁",
      "\n  intro h\n  have h₁ : rule ∈ (RelInt.liftFinf n f) := h\n  have h₂ : ∃ (i : Fin n) (j : Fin (f i).length), rule = (f i).get j := by\n    have h₃ : rule ∈ (RelInt.liftFinf n f) := h₁\n    have h₄ : (RelInt.liftFinf n f) = (fin_range n).map f |>.flatten := rfl\n    rw [h₄] at h₃\n    -- Now we know that rule is in the flattened list of (fin_range n).map f\n    -- We need to find i : Fin n and j : Fin (f i).length such that rule = (f i).get j\n    have h₅ : rule ∈ ( (fin_range n).map f |>.flatten ) := h₃\n    -- Use the fact that if an element is in the flattened list, it is in one of the sublists\n    have h₆ : ∃ (i : Fin n), rule ∈ (f i) := by\n      -- Use the property of flatten to find the sublist\n      have h₇ : ∀ {α : Type} (l : List (List α)) (x : α), x ∈ l.flatten → ∃ (l' : List α), l' ∈ l ∧ x ∈ l' := by\n        intro α l x hx\n        -- Prove that if x is in the flattened list, then it is in one of the sublists\n        have h₈ : x ∈ l.flatten := hx\n        have h₉ : ∃ (l' : List α), l' ∈ l ∧ x ∈ l' := by\n          -- Use the fact that x is in the flattened list to find the sublist\n          induction l with\n          | nil =>\n            -- If the list is empty, then x cannot be in the flattened list\n            exfalso\n            simp_all\n          | cons hd tl ih =>\n            -- If the list is not empty, check if x is in hd or in one of the sublists of tl\n            by_cases h₁₀ : x ∈ hd\n            · -- If x is in hd, then we can take l' = hd\n              exact ⟨hd, by simp, h₁₀⟩\n            · -- If x is not in hd, then check if x is in one of the sublists of tl\n              have h₁₁ : x ∈ (tl).flatten := by\n                simp [List.flatten_cons, h₁₀] at h₈ ⊢\n                <;> aesop\n              -- Use the induction hypothesis to find the sublist in tl\n              obtain ⟨l', h₁₂, h₁₃⟩ := ih h₁₁\n              exact ⟨l', by simp [h₁₂], h₁₃⟩\n        exact h₉\n      -- Apply the property to our case\n      have h